# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: koka-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] In computing, an **effect system** is a formal system that describes the computational effects of computer programs, such as side effects.
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] An effect system can be used to provide a compile-time check of the possible effects of the program.
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] The effect system extends the notion of type to have an "effect" component, which comprises an **effect kind** and a **region**.
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] The effect kind describes *what* is being done, and the region describes *with what* (parameters) it is being done.
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] An effect system is typically an extension of a type system.
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] The term "**type and effect system**" is sometimes used in this case.
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] Often, a type of a value is denoted together with its effect as *type ! effect*, where both the type component and the effect component mention certain regions (for example, a type of a mutable memory cell is parameterized by the label of the memory region in which the cell resides).
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] The term "algebraic effect" follows from the type system.
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] From a programmer's point of view, effects are useful as it allows for separating the implementation (*how*) of specific actions from the specification of what actions to perform.
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] For example, an *ask name* effect can read from either the console, pop a window, or just return a default value.
[src:koka-language/algebraic-effect] The control flow can be described as a blend of *yield* (in that the execution continues) and *throw* (in that an unhandled effect propagates down until handled).
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] In functional programming, **continuation-passing style** (**CPS**) is a style of programming in which control is passed explicitly in the form of a continuation.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] This is contrasted with *direct style*, which is the usual style of programming.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Steele, Jr. coined the phrase in AI Memo 349 (1975), which sets out the first version of the Scheme programming language.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Reynolds gives a detailed account of the many discoveries of continuations.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] A function written in continuation-passing style takes an extra argument: an explicit *continuation*; i.e., a function of one argument.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] When the CPS function has computed its result value, it "returns" it by calling the continuation function with this value as the argument.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] That means that when invoking a CPS function, the calling function is required to supply a procedure to be invoked with the subroutine's "return" value.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Expressing code in this form makes a number of things explicit which are implicit in direct style.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Programs can be automatically transformed from direct style to CPS.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Compilers for functional and logic programming languages often use CPS as an intermediate representation where a compiler for an imperative or procedural programming language would use static single assignment form (SSA).
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] SSA is formally equivalent to a subset of CPS (excluding non-local control flow, which does not occur when CPS is used as intermediate representation).
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Functional compilers can also use A-normal form (ANF) (but only for languages requiring eager evaluation), rather than with *thunks* (described in the examples below) in CPS.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] CPS is used more frequently by compilers than by programmers as a local or global style.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] In CPS, each procedure takes an extra argument representing what should be done with the result the function is calculating.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] This, along with a restrictive style prohibiting a variety of constructs usually available, is used to expose the semantics of programs, making them easier to analyze.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] This style also makes it easy to express unusual control structures, like `catch/throw` or other non-local transfers of control.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] The key to CPS is to remember that (a) *every* function takes an extra argument known as its continuation, and (b) every argument in a function call must be either a variable or a lambda expression (not a more complex expression).
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] This has the effect of turning expressions "inside-out" because the innermost parts of the expression must be evaluated first, thus CPS makes explicit the order of evaluation as well as the control flow.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Some examples of code in direct style and the corresponding CPS appear below.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] To call a procedure written in CPS from a procedure written in direct style, it is necessary to provide a continuation that will receive the result computed by the CPS procedure.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] In the example above (assuming that CPS primitives have been provided), we might call `(factorial& 10 (lambda (x) (display x) (newline)))`.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] There is some variety between compilers in the way primitive functions are provided in CPS.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Similarly, sometimes the `if` primitive is not included in CPS, and instead a function `if&` is provided which takes three arguments: a Boolean condition and the two thunks corresponding to the two arms of the conditional.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] The translations shown above show that CPS is a global transformation.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] The direct-style *factorial* takes, as might be expected, a single argument; the CPS *factorial&* takes two: the argument and a continuation.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Any function calling a CPS-ed function must either provide a new continuation or pass its own; any calls from a CPS-ed function to a non-CPS function will use implicit continuations.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Thus, to ensure the total absence of a function stack, the entire program must be in CPS.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] A function `pyth` to calculate a hypotenuse using the Pythagorean theorem can be written in Haskell.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] To transform the traditional function to CPS, its signature must be changed.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] First we calculate the square of *a* in `pyth'` function and pass a lambda function as a continuation which will accept a square of *a* as a first argument.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] And so on until the result of the calculations are reached.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] To get the result of this function we can pass `id` function as a final argument which returns the value that was passed to it unchanged: `pyth' 3 4 id == 5.0`.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] The mtl library, which is shipped with Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC), has the module `Control.Monad.Cont`.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] This module provides the Cont type, which implements Monad and some other useful functions.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Not only has the syntax become cleaner, but this type allows us to use a function `callCC` with type `MonadCont m => ((a -> m b) -> m a) -> m a`.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] This function has one argument of a function type; that function argument accepts the function too, which discards all computations going after its call.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Programming with continuations can also be useful when a caller does not want to wait until the callee completes.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] For example, in user interface (UI) programming, a routine can set up dialog box fields and pass these, along with a continuation function, to the UI framework.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] This call returns right away, allowing the application code to continue while the user interacts with the dialog box.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Once the user presses the "OK" button, the framework calls the continuation function with the updated fields.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Although this style of coding uses continuations, it is not full CPS.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] A similar idea can be used when the function must run in a different thread or on a different processor.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] The framework can execute the called function in a worker thread, then call the continuation function in the original thread with the worker's results.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Every call in CPS is a tail call, and the continuation is explicitly passed.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Using CPS without *tail call optimization* (TCO) will cause both the constructed continuation to potentially grow during recursion, and the call stack.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] This is usually undesirable, but has been used in interesting ways; see the Chicken Scheme compiler.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] As CPS and TCO eliminate the concept of an implicit function return, their combined use can eliminate the need for a run-time stack.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Several compilers and interpreters for functional programming languages use this ability in novel ways.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Continuation passing style can be used to implement continuations and control flow operators in a functional language that does not feature first-class continuations but does have first-class functions and tail-call optimization.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Without tail-call optimization, techniques such as trampolining, i.e., using a loop that iteratively invokes thunk-returning functions, can be used; without first-class functions, it is even possible to convert tail calls into just gotos in such a loop.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Writing code in CPS, while not impossible, is often error-prone.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] There are various translations, usually defined as one- or two-pass conversions of pure lambda calculus, which convert direct style expressions into CPS expressions.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Writing in trampolined style, however, is extremely difficult; when used, it is usually the target of some sort of transformation, such as compilation.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] A CPS transform is conceptually a Yoneda embedding.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] It is also similar to the embedding of lambda calculus in π-calculus.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Outside of computer science, CPS is of more general interest as an alternative to the conventional method of composing simple expressions into complex expressions.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] For example, within linguistic semantics, Chris Barker and his collaborators have suggested that specifying the denotations of sentences using CPS might explain certain phenomena in natural language.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] In mathematics, the Curry–Howard isomorphism between computer programs and mathematical proofs relates continuation-passing style translation to a variation of double-negation embeddings of classical logic into intuitionistic (constructive) logic.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Unlike the regular double-negation translation, which maps atomic propositions *p* to ((*p* → ⊥) → ⊥), the continuation passing style replaces ⊥ by the type of the final expression.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Accordingly, the result is obtained by passing the identity function as a continuation to the CPS expression, as in the above example.
[src:koka-language/continuation-passing-style] Classical logic itself relates to manipulating the continuation of programs directly, as in Scheme's call-with-current-continuation control operator, an observation due to Tim Griffin (using the closely related C control operator).
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] In programming languages, a **delimited continuation**, **composable continuation** or **partial continuation**, is a "slice" of a continuation frame that has been reified into a function.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Unlike regular continuations, delimited continuations return a value, and thus may be reused and composed.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Delimited continuations were first introduced by Felleisen in 1988 with an operator called ${\mathcal {F}}$ , first introduced in a tech report in 1987, along with a prompt construct $\#$ .
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The operator was designed to be a generalization of control operators that had been described in the literature such as `call/cc` from Scheme, ISWIM's J operator, John C.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Reynolds' `escape` operator, and others.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Subsequently, many competing delimited control operators were invented by the programming languages research community such as `prompt` and `control`, `shift` and `reset`,`cupto`, `fcontrol`, and others.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Various operators for delimited continuations have been proposed in the research literature.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] One independent proposal is based on continuation-passing style (CPS)—i.e., not on continuation frames—and offers two control operators, `shift` and `reset`, that give rise to static rather than to dynamic delimited continuations.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The `reset` operator sets the limit for the continuation while the `shift` operator captures or reifies the current continuation up to the innermost enclosing `reset`.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The `reset` delimits the continuation that `shift` captures (named by `k` in this example).
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] When this snippet is executed, the use of `shift` will bind `k` to the continuation `(+ 1 [])` where `[]` represents the part of the computation that is to be filled with a value.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] This continuation directly corresponds to the code that surrounds the `shift` up to the `reset`.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] In general, these operators can encode more interesting behavior by, for example, returning the captured continuation `k` as a value or invoking `k` multiple times.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The `shift` operator passes the captured continuation `k` to the code in its body, which can either invoke it, produce it as a result, or ignore it entirely.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Whatever result that `shift` produces is provided to the innermost `reset`, discarding the continuation in between the `reset` and `shift`.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] However, if the continuation is invoked, then it effectively re-installs the continuation after returning to the `reset`.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] When the entire computation within `reset` is completed, the result is returned by the delimited continuation.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] whenever `CODE` invokes `(k N)`, `(* 2 N)` is evaluated and returned.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Furthermore, once the entire computation within `shift` is completed, the continuation is discarded, and execution restarts outside `reset`.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] invokes `(k 4)` first (which returns 8), and then `(k 8)` (which returns 16).
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] At this point, the `shift` expression has terminated, and the rest of the `reset` expression is discarded.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Everything that happens outside the `reset` expression is hidden, i.e. not influenced by the control transfer.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Delimited continuations were first described independently by Felleisen *et al.* and Johnson.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] They have since been used in a large number of domains, particularly in defining new control operators; see Queinnec for a survey.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Let's take a look at a more complicated example.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The context captured by `shift` is `(begin [*] null)`, where `[*]` is the hole where `k`'s parameter will be injected.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The first call of `k` inside `shift` evaluates to this context with `(void)` = `#<void>` replacing the hole, so the value of `(k (void))` is `(begin #<void> null)` = `null`.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The body of `shift`, namely `(cons 1 null)` = `(1)`, becomes the overall value of the `reset` expression as the final result.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] This is pretty familiar, and can be rewritten as `(cons 1 (list 2))`, that is, `(list 1 2)`.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The part between `reset` and `shift` includes control functions like `lambda` and `for-each`; this is impossible to rephrase using lambdas.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] Delimited continuations are also useful in linguistics: see Continuations in linguistics for details.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The generalized curry function is given an uncurried function `f` and its arity (say, 3), and it returns the value of `(lambda (v1) (lambda (v2) (lambda (v3) (f v1 v2 v3))))`.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] This example is due to Olivier Danvy and was worked out in the mid-1980s.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] These unit tests verify whether currying the variadic function `+` into an n-ary curried function and applying the result to n arguments yields the same result as applying `+` to these n arguments, for n = 0, 1, 2, 3, and 4.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The following recursive function is accumulator-based and eventually reverses the accumulator before applying the given uncurried function.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] which delta-reduces to the result, `11`.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The following recursive function is continuation-based and involves no list reversal.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The following recursive function, `curry_d`, is the direct-style counterpart of `curry_c` and features the `(shift k k)` idiom, using Andrzej Filinski's implementation of shift and reset in terms of a global mutable cell and of `call/cc`.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The heart of the matter is the observational equivalence between `(reset (...
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] (shift k k) ...))` and `(lambda (x) (reset (... x ...)))` where `x` is fresh and the ellipses represent a pure context, i.e., one without control effects.
[src:koka-language/delimited-continuation] The definition of `curry_d` also illustrates static delimited continuations.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] Between 2010 and 2018, 154,000 AI patents were filed worldwide, with Microsoft having the largest percentage of those patents, at 20%.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] According to estimates in trade publications, Microsoft spent about $6 billion annually in research initiatives from 2002 to 2010 and has spent from $10–14 billion annually since 2010.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] Microsoft Research has made significant advances in the field of AI which it has infused in its products including Kinect, Bing, HoloLens, Cortana, Microsoft Translator, LinkedIn, Havok and Dynamics.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] Microsoft Research includes the core Microsoft Research labs and Microsoft Research AI, Microsoft Research NExT (for New Experiences and Technologies), and other incubation efforts all directed by corporate vice president Peter Lee.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] Microsoft Research sponsors several research fellowships for faculty and graduate students in the field of computer science.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] Since 2016, Microsoft has partnered with Toyota Connected to research technology for telematics, data analytics and network security services.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] In October 2019, Microsoft partnered with Novartis to apply artificial intelligence to enhance personalized medicine research.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] In 2023, Microsoft signed a multi-year deal to collaborate with Syneos Health in development of a platform to leverage machine learning for the optimization of clinical trials.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] Microsoft's "AI for Good" initiative represents a significant commitment to leveraging artificial intelligence technology for social and environmental benefits.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] This initiative is part of a broader vision by Microsoft to utilize AI in addressing some of the world's most challenging issues, including those related to health, the environment, accessibility, cultural heritage, and humanitarian action.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] AI for Good includes topics like Microsoft AI for Earth.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] Microsoft Azure Quantum has researched quantum information science since 2000 and is developing a topological quantum computer based on Majorana zero modes.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] In 2000, physicist Alexei Kitaev at Microsoft Research proposed developing a topological quantum computer from Majorana quasiparticles.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] In 2002, Michael Freedman, who led Microsoft's quantum research at Station Q in 2005, authored a paper with Kitaev demonstrating how a topological quantum computer could perform any computation that a conventional quantum computer could.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] In 2005, 2006 and 2008, Sankar Das Sarma, Freedman and Chetan Nayak developed theoretical proposals for a topological qubit using the fractional quantum Hall effect and for topological quantum computing based on non-abelian anyons.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] In 2015, Microsoft developed the theoretical framework of Majorana zero modes for information processing through braiding-based topological quantum computing.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] In 2023, Microsoft research demonstrated the creation and control of Majorana quasiparticles for topological quantum computing.
[src:koka-language/microsoft-research] In 2024, Microsoft created 4 logical qubits from 30 physical qubits, demonstrating reliable logical qubits by reducing the logical error rate by 800x compared to the physical error rate.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] In computer science, **region-based memory management** is a type of memory management in which each allocated object is assigned to a **region**.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] A region, also called a **partition**, **subpool**, **zone**, **arena**, **area**, or **memory context**, is a collection of allocated objects that can be efficiently reallocated or deallocated all at once.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Memory allocators using region-based managements are often called **area allocators**, and when they work by only "bumping" a single pointer, as **bump allocators**.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Like stack allocation, regions facilitate allocation and deallocation of memory with low overhead; but they are more flexible, allowing objects to live longer than the stack frame in which they were allocated.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] In typical implementations, all objects in a region are allocated in a single contiguous range of memory addresses, similarly to how stack frames are typically allocated.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] In OS/360 and successors, the concept applies at two levels; each job runs within a contiguous partition or region.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Storage allocation requests specify a subpool, and the application can free an entire subpool.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Storage for a subpool is allocated from the region or partition in blocks that are a multiple of 2 KiB or 4 KiB that generally are not contiguous.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] As a simple example, consider the following C++ code, which implements a simple compile-time arena, and a simple data type consisting of a string and an integer value.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Simple explicit regions are straightforward to implement; the following description is based on the work of Hanson.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Each region is implemented as a linked list of large blocks of memory; each block should be large enough to serve many allocations.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] The current block maintains a pointer to the next free position in the block, and if the block is filled, a new one is allocated and added to the list.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] When the region is deallocated, the next-free-position pointer is reset to the beginning of the first block, and the list of blocks can be reused for the next allocated region.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Alternatively, when a region is deallocated, its list of blocks can be appended to a global freelist from which other regions may later allocate new blocks.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] With either case of this simple scheme, it is not possible to deallocate individual objects in regions.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] The overall cost per allocated byte of this scheme is very low; almost all allocations involve only a comparison and an update to the next-free-position pointer.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Deallocating a region is a constant-time operation, and is done rarely.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Unlike in typical garbage collection systems, there is no need to tag data with its type.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] The basic concept of regions is very old, first appearing as early as 1967 in Douglas T.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Ross's AED Free Storage Package, in which memory was partitioned into a hierarchy of zones; each zone had its own allocator, and a zone could be freed all-at-once, making zones usable as regions.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] In 1976, the PL/I standard included the AREA data type.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] In 1990, Hanson demonstrated that explicit regions in C (which he called arenas) could achieve time performance per allocated byte superior to even the fastest-known heap allocation mechanism.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Explicit regions were instrumental in the design of some early C-based software projects, including the Apache HTTP Server, which calls them pools, and the PostgreSQL database management system, which calls them memory contexts.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Like traditional heap allocation, these schemes do not provide memory safety; it is possible for a programmer to access a region after it is deallocated through a dangling pointer, or to forget to deallocate a region, causing a memory leak.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] The compiler is able to do this in such a way that it can guarantee dangling pointers and leaks do not occur.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] In an early work by Ruggieri and Murtagh, a region is created at the beginning of each function and deallocated at the end.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] They then use data flow analysis to determine a lifetime for each static allocation expression, and assign it to the youngest region that contains its entire lifetime.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Due to this syntactic structure, regions are *nested*, meaning that if $r_{2}$ is created after $r_{1}$ , it must also be deallocated before $r_{1}$ ; the result is a *stack* of regions.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Moreover, regions must be deallocated in the same function in which they are created.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] These restrictions were relaxed by Aiken et al.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] This work was completed in 1995 and integrated into the ML Kit, a version of ML based on region allocation in place of garbage collection.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] This permitted a direct comparison between the two on medium-sized test programs, yielding widely varying results ("between 10 times faster and four times slower") depending on how "region-friendly" the program was; compile times, however, were on the order of minutes.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] The ML Kit was eventually scaled to large applications with two additions: a scheme for separate compilation of modules, and a hybrid technique combining region inference with tracing garbage collection.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Systems using regions may experience issues where regions become very large before they are deallocated and contain a large proportion of dead data; these are commonly called "leaks" (even though they are eventually freed).
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Eliminating leaks may involve restructuring the program, typically by introducing new, shorter-lifetime regions.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Debugging this type of problem is especially difficult in systems using region inference, where the programmer must understand the underlying inference algorithm, or examine the verbose intermediate representation, to diagnose the issue.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Tracing garbage collectors are more effective at deallocating this type of data in a timely manner without program changes; this was one justification for hybrid region/GC systems.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] On the other hand, tracing garbage collectors can also exhibit subtle leaks, if references are retained to data which will never be used again.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Region-based memory management works best when the number of regions is relatively small and each contains many objects; programs that contain many sparse regions will exhibit internal fragmentation, leading to wasted memory and a time overhead for region management.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Again, in the presence of region inference this problem can be more difficult to diagnose.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] As mentioned above, RC uses a hybrid of regions and reference counting, limiting the overhead of reference counting since references internal to regions don't require counts to be updated when they're modified.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] Similarly, some *mark-region* hybrid methods combine tracing garbage collection with regions; these function by dividing the heap into regions, performing a mark-sweep pass in which any regions containing live objects are marked, and then freeing any unmarked regions.
[src:koka-language/region-based-memory-management] These require continual defragmentation to remain effective.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In type theory, **type inference** (sometimes called **type reconstruction**) is the automatic detection of the type of an expression.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] These include programming languages and mathematical type systems, but also natural languages in some branches of computer science and linguistics.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In a typed language, a term's type determines the ways it can and cannot be used in that language.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] At best it might be metaphor; bending type rules is a feature of poetic language.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] A term's type can also affect the interpretation of operations involving that term.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] For instance, "a song" is of composable type, so we interpret it as the thing created in the phrase "write a song".
[src:koka-language/type-inference] On the other hand, "a friend" is of recipient type, so we interpret it as the addressee in the phrase "write a friend".
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In normal language, we would be surprised if "write a song" meant addressing a letter to a song or "write a friend" meant drafting a friend on paper.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Terms with different types can even refer to materially the same thing.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] For example, we would interpret "to hang up the clothes line" as putting it into use, but "to hang up the leash" as putting it away, even though, in context, both "clothes line" and "leash" might refer the same rope, just at different times.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Typings are often used to prevent an object from being considered too generally.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] For instance, if the type system treats all numbers as the same, then a programmer who accidentally writes code where `4` is supposed to mean "4 seconds" but is interpreted as "4 meters" would have no warning of their mistake until it caused problems at runtime.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] By incorporating units into the type system, these mistakes can be detected much earlier.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] As another example, Russell's paradox arises when anything can be a set element and any predicate can define a set, but more careful typing gives several ways to resolve the paradox.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In fact, Russell's paradox sparked early versions of type theory.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Especially in programming languages, there may not be much shared background knowledge available to the computer.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In manifestly typed languages, this means that most types have to be declared explicitly.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Type inference aims to alleviate this burden, freeing the author from declaring types that the computer should be able to deduce from context.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In a typing, an expression E is opposed to a type T, formally written as E : T.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Usually a typing only makes sense within some context, which is omitted here.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] If there is a way to derive a type for E, then we have accomplished *type inference*.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Given only a type, is there any expression for it or does the type have no values?
[src:koka-language/type-inference] For the simply typed lambda calculus, all three questions are decidable.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The situation is not as comfortable when more expressive types are allowed.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Types are a feature present in some strongly statically typed languages.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] It is often characteristic of functional programming languages in general.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The majority of them use a simple form of type inference; the Hindley–Milner type system can provide more complete type inference.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The ability to infer types automatically makes many programming tasks easier, leaving the programmer free to omit type annotations while still permitting type checking.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In some programming languages, all values have a data type explicitly declared at compile time, limiting the values a particular expression can take on at run-time.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Increasingly, just-in-time compilation blurs the distinction between run time and compile time.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] However, historically, if the type of a value is known only at run-time, these languages are dynamically typed.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In other languages, the type of an expression is known only at compile time; these languages are statically typed.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In most statically typed languages, the input and output types of functions and local variables ordinarily must be explicitly provided by type annotations.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The signature of this function definition, `int increment(int x)`, declares that `increment()` is a function that takes one argument, an integer, and returns an integer.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] `int result;` declares that the local variable `result` is an integer.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] This is identical to how code is written in the language Dart, except that it is subject to some added constraints as described below.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] It would be possible to *infer* the types of all the variables at compile time.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In the example above, the compiler would infer that `result` and `x` have type integer since the constant `1` is type integer, and hence that `increment()` is a function `int -> int`.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The variable `result2` isn't used in a legal manner, so it wouldn't have a type.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In the imaginary language in which the last example is written, the compiler would assume that, in the absence of information to the contrary, `+` takes two integers and returns one integer.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] (This is how it works in, for example, OCaml.) From this, the type inferencer can infer that the type of `x + 1` is an integer, which means `result` is an integer and thus the return value of `add_one` is an integer.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Similarly, since `+` requires both of its arguments be of the same type, `x` must be an integer, and thus, `add_one` accepts one integer as an argument.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] However, in the subsequent line, `result2` is calculated by adding a decimal `1.0` with floating-point arithmetic, causing a conflict in the use of `x` for both integer and floating-point expressions.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The correct type-inference algorithm for such a situation has been known since 1958 and has been known to be correct since 1982.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] It revisits the prior inferences and uses the most general type from the outset: in this case floating-point.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] This can however have detrimental implications, for instance using a floating-point from the outset can introduce precision issues that would have not been there with an integer type.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Frequently, however, degenerate type-inference algorithms are used that cannot backtrack and instead generate an error message in such a situation.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] This behavior may be preferable as type inference may not always be neutral algorithmically, as illustrated by the prior floating-point precision issue.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] An algorithm of intermediate generality implicitly declares `result2` as a floating-point variable, and the addition implicitly converts `x` to a floating point.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] This can be correct if the calling contexts never supply a floating point argument.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Such a situation shows the difference between *type inference*, which does not involve type conversion, and implicit type conversion, which forces data to a different data type, often without restrictions.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Finally, a significant downside of complex type-inference algorithm is that the resulting type inference resolution is not going to be obvious to humans (notably because of the backtracking), which can be detrimental as code is primarily intended to be comprehensible to humans.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The recent emergence of just-in-time compilation allows for hybrid approaches where the type of arguments supplied by the various calling context is known at compile time, and can generate a large number of compiled versions of the same function.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Each compiled version can then be optimized for a different set of types.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] A version that accepts an integer input and uses implicit type conversion.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] A version that accepts a floating-point number as input and uses floating point instructions throughout.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:koka-language/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:koka-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
